    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; line-height:1.8; color:#4a4540; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
      I know Wakerley well. I understand the buyer profile, the value of block size in this corridor, and how to position an executive family home to attract genuine competition from across the eastern and inner-east markets.
    </p>
    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; line-height:1.8; color:#4a4540; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
      Wakerley's residential character has settled into something distinct from its neighbours. Most of the suburb is two-storey brick-and-render or rendered hebel homes on 500 to 700 square metre blocks, with a strong concentration of homes built between 1998 and 2012 around the central estate streets. The newer pockets along the Gumdale boundary have continued to attract upgraders, and the Wakerley Park and Wakerley Tavern precinct gives the suburb a genuine local hub. Westfield Carindale sits ten minutes west, the Manly and Wynnum foreshores ten minutes east, and the Gateway Motorway entry at Tingalpa puts the airport and the CBD within practical commuting reach. That combination keeps the suburb's family demand consistent.
    </p>
    <div style="display:flex; gap:1.5rem; flex-wrap:wrap;">
      <div style="flex:1; min-width:200px; background:#fff; padding:1.75rem; border-left:3px solid #b98229; border-radius:16px;">
